he militants could move Alan after the US launched its first air strikes in Syria aimed at Isis strongholds.</p> \n<p>Colin Livesey said he feared Henning’s whereabouts would be unknown once more if he was moved. “I don’t want to lose the faith in knowing he’s coming home,” he told ITV News.</p> \n<p>One of the areas targeted by US was Raqqa – an Isis stronghold where Henning is believed to be held.</p> \n<p>Livesey described his brother-in-law as an “amazing bloke … a genuine, down-to-earth guy” who was a loving husband and father to his two children.</p> \n<p>“He thought he was doing the right thing by going up there and helping other people in another country, to give them aid, because that’s the sort of guy he is … he doesn’t deserve what’s happening to him now,” he said.</p> \n<p>“He’s so passionate about what he does and that makes us so proud of him. To do it at Christmas, to miss his own family Christmas to go to Syria, speaks volumes of what a man he is.”</p> \n<p>David Cameron, who is in New York attending the annual UN gathering of world leaders, has backed the air strikes. They were ordered by the US president, Barack Obama, after intelligence reports indicated that an attack by an organisation linked to al-Qaida called the Khorasan group was “imminent”.</p>"},"type":"text"}],"bodyTextSummary":"The wife of Alan Henning, the British aid worker kidnapped by Islamic State (Isis) militants, has made a new plea for his release after being sent an audio recording of her husband on Tuesday. Barbara Henning said that Alan was “pleading for his life” in the recording. Islamic State had ignored requests by her representatives to open negotiations about the fate of her husband, who was seized in Syria in 2012. “I have seen Muslims across the globe question Islamic State over Alan’s fate,” her statement read. “The voices of the people have spoken out loud and clear. He was working with Muslims to help the most vulnerable within Syria. Nothing has changed. He went to Syria to help his Muslim friends deliver much-needed aid. “We are at a loss why those leading Islamic State cannot open their hearts and minds to the facts surrounding Alan’s imprisonment and why they continue to threaten his life.” Barbara Henning said she had been told that her husband had been found innocent of being a spy by a sharia court. “I implore Islamic State to abide by the decisions of their own justice system. Please release Alan,” she added. Earlier, Henning’s brother-in-law said he feared the militants could move Alan after the US launched its first air strikes in Syria aimed at Isis strongholds. Colin Livesey said he feared Henning’s whereabouts would be unknown once more if he was moved. “I don’t want to lose the faith in knowing he’s coming home,” he told ITV News. One of the areas targeted by US was Raqqa – an Isis stronghold where Henning is believed to be held. Livesey described his brother-in-law as an “amazing bloke … a genuine, down-to-earth guy” who was a loving husband and father to his two children. “He thought he was doing the right thing by going up there and helping other people in another country, to give them aid, because that’s the sort of guy he is … he doesn’t deserve what’s happening to him now,” he said. “He’s so passionate about what he does and that makes us so proud of him. To do it at Christmas, to miss his own family Christmas to go to Syria, speaks volumes of what a man he is.” David Cameron, who is in New York attending the annual UN gathering of world leaders, has backed the air strikes. They were ordered by the US president, Barack Obama, after intelligence reports indicated that an attack by an organisation linked to al-Qaida called the Khorasan group was “imminent”.","bodyHtml":"<p>The wife of Alan Henning, the British aid worker kidnapped by Islamic State (Isis) militants, has made a new plea for his release after being sent an audio recording of her husband on Tuesday.</p> <p>Barbara Henning said that Alan was “pleading for his life” in the recording.</p> <p>Islamic State had ignored requests by her representatives to open negotiations about the fate of her husband, who was seized in Syria in 2012.</p> <p>“I have seen Muslims across the globe question Islamic State over Alan’s fate,” her statement read. “The voices of the people have spoken out loud and clear. He was working with Muslims to help the most vulnerable within Syria. Nothing has changed. He went to Syria to help his Muslim friends deliver much-needed aid.</p> <p>“We are at a loss why those leading Islamic State cannot open their hearts and minds to the facts surrounding Alan’s imprisonment and why they continue to threaten his life.”</p> <p>Barbara Henning said she had been told that her husband had been found innocent of being a spy by a sharia court. “I implore Islamic State to abide by the decisions of their own justice system. Please release Alan,” she added.</p> <p>Earlier, Henning’s brother-in-law said he feared the militants could move Alan after the US launched its first air strikes in Syria aimed at Isis strongholds.</p> <p>Colin Livesey said he feared Henning’s whereabouts would be unknown once more if he was moved. “I don’t want to lose the faith in knowing he’s coming home,” he told ITV News.</p> <p>One of the areas targeted by US was Raqqa – an Isis stronghold where Henning is believed to be held.</p> <p>Livesey described his brother-in-law as an “amazing bloke … a genuine, down-to-earth guy” who was a loving husband and father to his two children.</p> <p>“He thought he was doing the right thing by going up there and helping other people in another country, to give them aid, because that’s the sort of guy he is … he doesn’t deserve what’s happening to him now,” he said.</p> <p>“He’s so passionate about what he does and that makes us so proud of him. To do it at Christmas, to miss his own family Christmas to go to Syria, speaks volumes of what a man he is.”</p> <p>David Cameron, who is in New York attending the annual UN gathering of world leaders, has backed the air strikes. They were ordered by the US president, Barack Obama, after intelligence reports indicated that an attack by an organisation linked to al-Qaida called the Khorasan group was “imminent”.</p>","attributes":{},"id":"4e28bdce-10f3-40a3-a32c-f1eacfd281f4","published":true,"contributors":[]}]},"webPublicationDate":"2014-09-23T20:16:08Z","fields":{"shouldHideAdverts":"false","wordcount":"425","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4xztn","secureThumbnail":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/9/23/1411503321033/Alan-Henning-at-a-refugee-004.jpg","main":"<figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-afef2bc4-bb40-4813-abb2-f74b182eae8c\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/9/23/1411503326711/Alan-Henning-at-a-refugee-009.jpg\" alt=\"Alan Henning at a refugee camp on the Turkish-Syrian border\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Alan Henning, the British aid worker kidnapped by Isis, at a refugee camp on the Turkish-Syrian border. Photograph: Reuters</span> </figcaption> </figure>","liveBloggingNow":"false","body":"<p>The wife of Alan Henning, the British aid worker kidnapped by Islamic State (Isis) militants, has made a new plea for his release after being sent an audio recording of her husband on Tuesday.</p> <p>Barbara Henning said that Alan was “pleading for his life” in the recording.</p> <p>Islamic State had ignored requests by her representatives to open negotiations about the fate of her husband, who was seized in Syria in 2012.</p> <p>“I have seen Muslims across the globe question Islamic State over Alan’s fate,” her statement read. “The voices of the people have spoken out loud and clear. He was working with Muslims to help the most vulnerable within Syria. Nothing has changed. He went to Syria to help his Muslim friends deliver much-needed aid.</p> <p>“We are at a loss why those leading Islamic State cannot open their hearts and minds to the facts surrounding Alan’s imprisonment and why they continue to threaten his life.”</p> <p>Barbara Henning said she had been told that her husband had been found innocent of being a spy by a sharia court. “I implore Islamic State to abide by the decisions of their own justice system. Please release Alan,” she added.</p> <p>Earlier, Henning’s brother-in-law said he feared the militants could move Alan after the US launched its first air strikes in Syria aimed at Isis strongholds.</p> <p>Colin Livesey said he feared Henning’s whereabouts would be unknown once more if he was moved. “I don’t want to lose the faith in knowing he’s coming home,” he told ITV News.</p> <p>One of the areas targeted by US was Raqqa – an Isis stronghold where Henning is believed to be held.</p> <p>Livesey described his brother-in-law as an “amazing bloke … a genuine, down-to-earth guy” who was a loving husband and father to his two children.</p> <p>“He thought he was doing the right thing by going up there and helping other people in another country, to give them aid, because that’s the sort of guy he is … he doesn’t deserve what’s happening to him now,” he said.</p> <p>“He’s so passionate about what he does and that makes us so proud of him. To do it at Christmas, to miss his own family Christmas to go to Syria, speaks volumes of what a man he is.”</p> <p>David Cameron, who is in New York attending the annual UN gathering of world leaders, has backed the air strikes. They were ordered by the US president, Barack Obama, after intelligence reports indicated that an attack by an organisation linked to al-Qaida called the Khorasan group was “imminent”.</p>","internalOctopusCode":"9560494","productionOffice":"UK","newspaperEditionDate":"2014-09-24T00:00:00Z","hasStoryPackage":"true","internalPageCode":"2163452","internalRevision":"6","publication":"The Guardian","trailText":"Barbara Henning receives reco