references":[]},{"id":"theguardian/mainsection","webTitle":"Main section","type":"newspaper-book","sectionId":"news","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/mainsection","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/theguardian/mainsection","sectionName":"News","references":[]}],"references":[]},{"id":"world/2014/sep/23/fears-isis-hostage-alan-henning-us-air-strikes-syria","rights":{"syndicatable":"true"},"type":"article","sectionId":"world","webTitle":"Fears for Isis hostage Alan Henning after US air strikes in Syria","blocks":{"body":[{"createdDate":"2014-09-23T19:34:39.157+01:00","lastModifiedDate":"2014-09-23T19:38:25.705+01:00","createdBy":{"firstName":"incopy","lastName":"integration","email":"incopyIntegration@guardian.co.uk"},"lastModifiedBy":{"firstName":"incopy","lastName":"integration","email":"incopyIntegration@guardian.co.uk"},"elements":[{"assets":[],"textTypeData":{"html":"<p>The brother-in-law of Alan Henning, the British aid volunteer kidnapped by Islamic State in 2012, has spoken of his fears over US air strikes in Syria aimed at the militants’ strongholds.</p> \n<p>Colin Livesey said on Tuesday he was concerned that the action could prompt Isis to move Henning and make his whereabouts unknown once more. “I don’t want to lose the faith in knowing he’s coming home,” he told ITV News.</p> \n<p>The United States had made the first air strikes on Syria overnight, with one of the areas reportedly hit being Raqqa – the Isis stronghold where Henning is believed to be held.</p> \n<p>Livesey described his brother-in-law as an “amazing bloke … a genuine, down-to-earth guy” who was a loving husband and father to his two children.</p> \n<p>“He thought he was doing the right thing by going up there and helping other people in another country, to give them aid, because that’s the sort of guy he is … he doesn’t deserve what’s happening to him now,” he said.</p> \n<p>“He’s so passionate about what he does and that makes us so proud of him. To do it at Christmas, to miss his own family Christmas to go to Syria, speaks volumes of what a man he is.”</p> \n<p>David Cameron, who is in New York attending the United Nations’ annual gathering of world leaders, has backed the air strikes. They were ordered by the US president, Barack Obama, after intelligence reports indicated that an attack by an organisation linked to al-Qaida called the Khorasan group was “imminent”.</p> \n<p>The prime minister is using the two-day meeting to muster support for international action against Isis and to discuss Britain’s contribution to the US-led coalition. Cameron is also expected to speak with Iranian president Hassan Rouhani – the first meeting between a British prime minister and a leader of Iran since the revolution of 1979 – in an attempt to enlist Tehran’s support.</p> \n<p>Obama has said the US will “do what’s necessary” to tackle the militants. Support for the campaign by five Arab states – Jordan, Qatar, Saudi Arabia, Bahrain and the United Arab Emirates – underlined the support he was building for international action against Isis, the president said.</p>"},"type":"text"}],"bodyTextSummary":"The brother-in-law of Alan Henning, the British aid volunteer kidnapped by Islamic State in 2012, has spoken of his fears over US air strikes in Syria aimed at the militants’ strongholds. Colin Livesey said on Tuesday he was concerned that the action could prompt Isis to move Henning and make his whereabouts unknown once more. “I don’t want to lose the faith in knowing he’s coming home,” he told ITV News. The United States had made the first air strikes on Syria overnight, with one of the areas reportedly hit being Raqqa – the Isis stronghold where Henning is believed to be held. Livesey described his brother-in-law as an “amazing bloke … a genuine, down-to-earth guy” who was a loving husband and father to his two children. “He thought he was doing the right thing by going up there and helping other people in another country, to give them aid, because that’s the sort of guy he is … he doesn’t deserve what’s happening to him now,” he said. “He’s so passionate about what he does and that makes us so proud of him. To do it at Christmas, to miss his own family Christmas to go to Syria, speaks volumes of what a man he is.” David Cameron, who is in New York attending the United Nations’ annual gathering of world leaders, has backed the air strikes. They were ordered by the US president, Barack Obama, after intelligence reports indicated that an attack by an organisation linked to al-Qaida called the Khorasan group was “imminent”. The prime minister is using the two-day meeting to muster support for international action against Isis and to discuss Britain’s contribution to the US-led coalition. Cameron is also expected to speak with Iranian president Hassan Rouhani – the first meeting between a British prime minister and a leader of Iran since the revolution of 1979 – in an attempt to enlist Tehran’s support. Obama has said the US will “do what’s necessary” to tackle the militants. Support for the campaign by five Arab states – Jordan, Qatar, Saudi Arabia, Bahrain and the United Arab Emirates – underlined the support he was building for international action against Isis, the president said.","bodyHtml":"<p>The brother-in-law of Alan Henning, the British aid volunteer kidnapped by Islamic State in 2012, has spoken of his fears over US air strikes in Syria aimed at the militants’ strongholds.</p> <p>Colin Livesey said on Tuesday he was concerned that the action could prompt Isis to move Henning and make his whereabouts unknown once more. “I don’t want to lose the faith in knowing he’s coming home,” he told ITV News.</p> <p>The United States had made the first air strikes on Syria overnight, with one of the areas reportedly hit being Raqqa – the Isis stronghold where Henning is believed to be held.</p> <p>Livesey described his brother-in-law as an “amazing bloke … a genuine, down-to-earth guy” who was a loving husband and father to his two children.</p> <p>“He thought he was doing the right thing by going up there and helping other people in another country, to give them aid, because that’s the sort of guy he is … he doesn’t deserve what’s happening to him now,” he said.</p> <p>“He’s so passionate about what he does and that makes us so proud of him. To do it at Christmas, to miss his own family Christmas to go to Syria, speaks volumes of what a man he is.”</p> <p>David Cameron, who is in New York attending the United Nations’ annual gathering of world leaders, has backed the air strikes. They were ordered by the US president, Barack Obama, after intelligence reports indicated that an attack by an organisation linked to al-Qaida called the Khorasan group was “imminent”.</p> <p>The prime minister is using the two-day meeting to muster support for international action against Isis and to discuss Britain’s contribution to the US-led coalition. Cameron is also expected to speak with Iranian president Hassan Rouhani – the first meeting between a British prime minister and a leader of Iran since the revolution of 1979 – in an attempt to enlist Tehran’s support.</p> <p>Obama has said the US will “do what’s necessary” to tackle the militants. Support for the campaign by five Arab states – Jordan, Qatar, Saudi Arabia, Bahrain and the United Arab Emirates – underlined the support he was building for international action against Isis, the president said.</p>","attributes":{},"id":"f9212a93-94ef-4532-88ce-13671f10216a","published":true,"contributors":[]}]},"webPublicationDate":"2014-09-23T18:38:27Z","fields":{"shouldHideAdverts":"false","wordcount":"366","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4xzhk","secureThumbnail":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/9/23/1411497451258/328a04f0-f439-4dee-97f2-b91686e22c67-140x84.jpeg","main":"<figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-9b94d5ca-94e9-4480-84a4-9dac0939a22e\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/